issue.body:
#### Summary
I like the recursive comparison strategy for `isEqualTo`. In addition I propose an new comparison strategy that works on public `getXXX()` methods. This makes it easy to compare beans with each other and at the same time also checking the getter implementations. This is especially useful when getters return `Optional`s, because I often found issue where `Optional.of()` was used when instead `Optional.ofNullable()` should have been used. Instead of writing a test for every single getter this could then be done with a single call.


#### Example

```java
public class Bean {
   private String s = null;
   
   public Optional<String> getS() { return Optional.of(s); } // coding error here
}

...
// This finds the error
assertThat(new Bean()).usingRecursiveBeanComparison().isEqualTo(new Bean());
```

#### Summary

When comparing values, AssertJ takes a very strong opinion that the objects are defined by their _fields_, which is contrary to general Java best practice and makes testing interface-based code difficult. It seems that AssertJ will internally use property-based access as some kind of fallback, but it has eager fast-fail on some very ordinary use cases.

Instead, AssertJ should _prefer_ property-based access when it's declared, and it should not perform invasive introspection if a perfectly suitable public property is available.


#### Example

```java
interface MailMessage {
  String getTemplate();
  InternetAddress getRecipient();
}

class HelloMessage implements MailMessage {
  @Override public final String getTemplate() { return "hello"; }
  @Getter @Setter InternetAddress recipient;
}

@Getter
@Setter
class GenericMessage implements MailMessage {
  String template;
  InternetAddress recipient;
}
```

In my code, I want to assert that, after processing, `var original = new HelloMessage()` and `var result // instanceof GenericMessage` have the same property values. However, trying to use `assertThat(result).usingRecursiveComparison().isEqualTo(original)` produces this error:

```
GenericMessage can't be compared to HelloMessage as  does not declare all GenericMessage fields, it lacks these: [template]
```

`template` is most certainly declared as a _property_, which is all that most infrastructure cares about, and the old `isEqualToComparingFieldByField`, even though named "field", handled this fine.

**Describe the bug**
RecursiveComparisonDifferenceCalculator is fetching field values preferred via property accessor and not via plain field reflection.
This becomes to an issue in case the property accessor is returning new instances on each invocation and a cyclic graph structure exists for comparison. In that case it might happen that RecursiveComparisonDifferenceCalculator (assertThat(...).usingRecursiveComparison()...) is ending up with an unexpected stackoverflow.

* assertj core version: 3.23.1 and previous versions (3.18.1)
* java version: 11
* test framework version: JUnit Jupiter 5.9.0
* os (if relevant): Windows 10

**Test case reproducing the bug**
See also attached [sandbox.zip](https://github.com/assertj/assertj/files/9584786/sandbox.zip). There is a single test class contained called "StackOverflowTest".

```java
package sandbox;

import static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;

import java.util.Collections;
import java.util.HashSet;
import java.util.Set;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;

/**
 * @author Philipp FÃ¶rmer
 *
 */
public class StackOverflowTest {

    /**
     * This test case will cause a stack overflow during reflection comparison, as the
     * {@link org.assertj.core.api.recursive.comparison.RecursiveComparisonDifferenceCalculator RecursiveComparisonDifferenceCalculator}
     * is fetching field values preferred via property accessor and not via plain field reflection.
     *
     * Scenario:
     * It is a simple cyclic graph constructed A1 &lt;-&gt; A2. A1 and A2 contain pointer collections to each other.
     * The getter of the pointer collection is only returning a copy of the pointer collection and not the plain instance.
     * So every access of the getter of the pointer collection is returning a new collection instance.
     * This will trick the RecursiveComparisonDifferenceCalculator visited DualValue collection, to not see an already visited field
     * as visited and cause stack overflow death.
     *
     * Possible solutions:
     * 1. Always use field reflection in RecursiveComparisonDifferenceCalculator, never make use of property getter reflection.
     *    Maybe this might not work reliable in case of proxy objects, where parts are initialized over getter access.
     *    This is for example problematic for JPA entity classes with annotations mapped by getters.
     * 2. Provide a configuration option for {@link org.assertj.core.api.recursive.comparison.RecursiveComparisonConfiguration RecursiveComparisonConfiguration}
     *    to enable/disable usage of property getter reflection. The default value should be to make use of plain field reflection.
     * 3. ...
     */
    @Test
    public void overflowDueToPropertyInspection() {
        final A actual = new A();
        final A a2 = new A();
        actual.add(a2);
        a2.add(actual);

        final A expected = new A();
        final A e2 = new A();
        expected.add(e2);
        e2.add(expected);

        assertThat(actual).usingRecursiveComparison()
            .ignoringCollectionOrder()
            .isEqualTo(expected);
    }


    private static class A {

        private Set<A> elements = new HashSet<>();

        public void add(final A a) {
            elements.add(a);
        }

        public Set<A> getElements() {
            return Collections.unmodifiableSet(elements);
        }
    }

}

```

Hi,

#### Summary
If you have a getter that modifies the value or only returns a subset of the value, the [current resolving strategy](https://assertj.github.io/doc/#how-field-values-are-resolved) is error prone / unusable for recursive comparison tests (see example below).
Perhaps it's possible to add the support to do the value resolution only by field via reflection? Perhabs a boolean configuration could override the [current implementation](https://github.com/assertj/assertj-core/blob/a49869bf382f19a3dd4ada49e655c07f90fab05a/src/main/java/org/assertj/core/util/introspection/PropertyOrFieldSupport.java#L70)?
Currently, we use the recursive comparison for all our tests and love the fact that new properties of a class are always tested immediately. Thanks for the new kind of testing ðŸ‘ðŸ¼ 

#### Example
Note: This is only an example to illustrate the problem. The easy solution would be the usage of "clean" getters. But if you have a public API you couldn't just change the internal behaviourâ€¦

```java
public class Example
{
    private Collection<String> value;

    public Example(Collection<String> value)
    {
        this.value = value;
    }

    public String getValue()
    {
        if (value == null)
        {
            return null;
        }
        return value.iterator().next();
    }
}

class ExampleTest
{
    @Test
    void testRecCom() // should fail
    {
        Assertions.assertThat(new Example(List.of("A", "B")))
                .usingRecursiveComparison()
                .ignoringAllOverriddenEquals()
                .withStrictTypeChecking()
                .isEqualTo(new Example(List.of("A")));
    }
}
```

Greetings!
